# 10) How Complex Projects Scale

---

## Pattern: Event-Driven Domains

```text
user.created        --> notifications
                    --> analytics
                    --> audit logs

payment.completed   --> invoices
                    --> rewards
                    --> reports
```

---

Each service binds its own queue.

No tight coupling.

---

---

# 11) Why Exchange-Centric Design Matters

Because queues are implementation details.

Exchanges define public contracts.

---

## If Queue Changes?

No producer changes needed.

Only bindings updated.

---

That is huge in production.

---

---

# 12) Best Practices

---

## Use Topic Exchanges for Flexibility

Better than direct in many systems.

---

---

## Standardize Routing Keys

Example:

```text
domain.entity.action
```

Like:

```text
user.account.created
billing.invoice.paid
```

---

---

## Use JSON Schema / Versioning

Include version.

```json
{
  "version": 1,
  "event": "user.created"
}
```

---

---

## Use Dead Letter Queues

For failures.

---

---

## Use Separate Exchanges by Domain

Avoid one giant exchange.

---

---

# Final Answer to Your Doubts

---

## Can we have multiple exchanges?

Yes. Common in production.

---

---

## Can we have multiple queues?

Yes. Essential for scaling.

---

---

## Can one exchange connect to many queues?

Yes.

---

---

## Can one queue receive from many exchanges?

Yes.

---

---

## Does routing key matter?

Absolutely. It controls routing.

---

---

## Does producer need queue info?

No—only exchange + routing key.

